Came looking to suggest the fix and good to see its already done  :+1:  .   Thanks for the fix. 
This is not only a memory issue.  Its causing considerable performance loss also.   
The internal hash bucket keeps growing as the protoreader is being recycled and the same dictionary used.
Eventually,  the clear method starts slowing down as it has to set all the buckets and entries to nil values.
Its a .Net Dictionary implementation issue but affecting the protoreader .
Since the protoreader is defined ThreadStatic ,  it occurs only if the same thread is used for multiple serialization and de-serialization with unique strings.
Below is the sample code to reproduce the issue.
      //Build some data.
        List<byte[]> bytes = new List<byte[]>();
        foreach (var item in Enumerable.Range(0, 100000))
        {
            var ms = new MemoryStream();
            Serializer.Serialize<string>(ms, item.ToString());
            bytes.Add(ms.ToArray());
        }

        // before the issue, try to deserialize it
        System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch sw = new System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch();
        sw.Start();
        foreach (var item in bytes) { var ret = Serializer.Deserialize<string>(new MemoryStream(item)); }
        sw.Stop();
        Console.WriteLine("Before:" + sw.ElapsedMilliseconds + " ms");

        // lets cause a lot of deserialization with unique strings
        var stream = new MemoryStream();
        IList<string> items = new List<string>();
        Enumerable.Range(0, 40000).ToList().ForEach((item) => items.Add(item.ToString()));
        Serializer.Serialize(stream, items);

        // deserialize . This will result in the interner dictionary internal buckets to grow.
       var test = Serializer.Deserialize<IList<string>>(new MemoryStream(stream.ToArray()));

          // after this , every stringInterner.Clear(); call is slow.
        // now we can see the delay
        System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch sw2 = new System.Diagnostics.Stopwatch();
        sw2.Start();
        foreach (var item in bytes) { var ret = Serializer.Deserialize<string>(new MemoryStream(item)); }
        sw2.Stop();
        Console.WriteLine("After :" + sw2.ElapsedMilliseconds +" ms");

        Console.ReadKey();

