The code is applying the DataMembers to the properties, without the ability to write to the backing variable. To fix this, we can do either of these:
1) Apply the DataMember to the backing variables (the contract will have lower case names):
```C#
[DataContract]
public class TestMessage
{
    [DataMember(Order = 1)]
    private readonly int clientId;
    public int ClientId
    {
        get { return clientId; }
    }
[DataMember(Order = 2)]
private readonly string name;
public string Name
{
    get { return name; }
}

public TestMessage()
{}

public TestMessage(int clientId, string name)
{
    this.clientId = clientId;
    this.name = name;
}

}
```
2) Use Auto-Properties instead:
```C#
[DataContract]
public class TestMessage
{
    [DataMember(Order = 1)]
    public int ClientId { get; private set; }
[DataMember(Order = 2)]
public string Name { get; private set; }

public TestMessage()
{ }

public TestMessage(int clientId, string name)
{
    ClientId = clientId;
    Name = name;
}

}
```
In either case, we also need a default constructor.
